In [4]:
# normalize images (you can also augment training dataset if needed here)
train_datagen = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(
        rescale=1./255,
        rotation_range=0,
        shear_range=0,
        zoom_range=0,
        vertical_flip=False,
        horizontal_flip=False)
valid_datagen = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)
test_datagen = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)
In [5]:
# specify variables
target_size = (224,224)
batch_size = 32
In [6]:
# create batches of tensor data
train_data_gen = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train,
    target_size=target_size, 
    batch_size=batch_size, 
    class_mode='binary')

valid_data_gen = valid_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    valid,
    target_size=target_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='binary',
    shuffle=False)

test_data_gen = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test,
    target_size=target_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='binary',
    shuffle=False)

In [8]:
# visualize batch of images
sample_training_images, labels = next(train_data_gen)

def plotImages(images_arr, labels):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 4, figsize=(15,15))
    axes = axes.flatten()
    for img, lbs, ax in zip( images_arr, labels, axes):
        ax.imshow(img)
        ax.set_title(class_labels[lbs])
        ax.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
plotImages(sample_training_images[:16], labels[:16])
In [9]:
# get base model, do not include the ImageNet classifier at the top
input_shape = (224,224,3)

base_model = tf.keras.applications.ResNet50(
    include_top=False,
    weights="imagenet",
    input_shape=input_shape
)
# freeze the base model    
base_model.trainable = False
In [10]:
# add your classifier to the base model
model = Sequential()
model.add(base_model)
model.add(GlobalMaxPooling2D())
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(1))
model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))

In [14]:
# compile and fit the model
model.compile(
    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(),
    loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(),
    metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.BinaryAccuracy()],
)

epochs = 20
model.fit(train_data_gen, epochs=epochs, validation_data=valid_data_gen)

In [19]:
# calculater sensitivity, specificity, positive predictive value, negative predictive value
cm = confusion_matrix(test_data_gen.classes, predictions)
TN = cm[0,0]
FP = cm[0,1]
FN = cm[1,0]
TP = cm[1,1]
sensitivity = (TP/(TP + FN))*100
specificity = (TN/(TN + FP))*100
PPV = (TP/(TP + FP))*100
NPV = (TN/(TN + FN))*100
print(f'Sensitivity:              {sensitivity: .2f}%')
print(f'Specificity:              {specificity: .2f}%')
print(f'Positive predictive value:{PPV: .2f}%')
print(f'Negative predictive value:{NPV: .2f}%')

Sensitivity:               77.50%
Specificity:               92.50%
Positive predictive value: 91.18%
Negative predictive value: 80.43%

In [33]:
# make prediction on single image
image_path = 'data/test/melanoma/melanoma8.jpg'

class_names = ['Malignant Melanoma', 'Benign Nevus']

img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(
    image_path, target_size=(224,224)
)
img_array = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(img)
img_array = tf.expand_dims(img_array, 0) # Create a batch

predictions = model.predict(img_array)
if predictions[0][0] < 0.5:
    print(f'This image most likely represents Malignant Melanoma')
else:
    print(f'This image most likely represents Benign Nevus')
print(predictions[0][0])
PIL.Image.open(image_path)

This image most likely represents Benign Nevus
